  #### First Past The Post

  Imagine a standard US election for a member of the House of
  Representatives. Multiple candidates can run for the single seat in
  the congressional district. The winner is the single candidate who
  receives the greatest number of votes.

  45% of votes are for Markov, 40% of votes are for Curie, and 15% of
  votes are for Gizmo. Markov wins the election and is elected
  congressperson. This happens even though fewer than 50% of voters
  voted for Markov.

  This kind of electoral system is called *First Past The Post*
  (abbreviated FPTP). In a FPTP system, the winner is the candidate who
  has received the *plurality* of the votes (the greatest number). It
  doesn't matter whether the winner has received a *majority* of the
  votes (that is, more than 50% of the votes cast).

  #### Wasted Votes, Voter Regret, Spoilers

  We might (cruelly) say that the voters for Gizmo have "wasted" their
  votes. They did not vote for either of the top-two candidates, so the
  Gizmo voters neither increased nor decreased Markov's margin of
  victory. In a sense, the Gizmo voters' participation was superfluous
  to the final result of the election.

  Perhaps the voters for Gizmo would have preferred that Curie be
  elected over Markov. For instance: perhaps Markov and Curie are right
  and left candidates, while Gizmo is a far-left candidate. The voters
  for Gizmo may *regret* their vote and wish that they had voted for
  Curie instead.

  If Gizmo's voters were able to switch their votes to Curie, Curie
  would win 55%-to-45%. Because Gizmo has pulled away enough voters from
  Curie so that she is in second-place (rather than the winner), we call
  Gizmo a *spoiler* candidate.

  The possibility for voter regret and spoiler candidates is a negative
  attribute of FPTP.

  #### Two-Round Systems

  Some electoral systems try to address this problem by using the
  *two-round* electoral system. Under this system, if no candidate
  receives a majority, then a *second* round is run. The second round
  consists of only the top two candidates from the first round.

  In our example, since neither Markov, Curie, nor Gizmo received a
  majority (more than 50% of votes), a second round would be run. The
  top two candidates in the first round were Markov and Curie, so they
  are selected for the second round. Presuming that the voters for Gizmo
  prefer Curie to Markov, Curie will win 55%-to-45%. Curie wins!

  The two round system tends to reduce "wasted" votes. Every vote in the
  second round either increases or decreases the winner's margin of
  victory -- no second round vote is wasted. Effectively, the two round
  system gives every voter a chance to change their vote to one of the
  top two candidates.

  A single third-party candidate cannot act as a spoiler in the two
  round system, since the potential spoiler is eliminated before the
  final second round. In a strongly two-party system (like in America),
  it is difficult for even multiple third-party candidates to spoil a
  two round election. We shall see, however, that spoiling is still
  possible if there is a strong third party!

  The two-round system is very commonly used throughout the world. It is
  almost universally used for electing the president of a country.
  France is the classic example.

  Most countries do not use single-member legislative districts at all,
  so neither FPTP nor two round systems are applicable. In those
  countries with single-member districts, FPTP is the more common
  option. However, France does elect its National Assembly members using
  the two-round system.

  #### Automating A Two Round System

  If there is no first-round majority winner, a second round wil have to
  be held. This means the electorate must come out on a second day to
  vote in a second election! Could we somehow streamline the two round
  system by eliminating the second round?

  The simplest solution is this: ask each voter to *rank* all candidates
  on the ballot. We then count all the first-rank votes. If there is a
  majority winner then they are elected and we are done.

  Otherwise we eliminate all but the top two candidates. In our example,
  Gizmo would be eliminated, since they are ranked first on only 15% of
  ballots. We then recount each ballot for the more preferred of the two
  remaining candidates. In our example, votes for Gizmo are
  "transferred" to Curie, who the Gizmo voters have ranked second.

  This system is called *contingent voting*. It is simply an
  "automation" of a standard two round system. I am not aware that
  contingent voting is used anywhere. That is because a better
  alternative exists.

