  What if a candidate would win every head-to-head matchup of
  candidates, but is *not* amongst the top-two candidates if you only
  consider voters' first choice? In such a scenario, both the two round
  and contingent voting systems would "prematurely" jump to eliminating
  all but the top-two first-choice candidates. This would be a "mistake"
  because an eliminated candidate would defeat either of the "top-two"
  candidates in a head-to-head election.

  A fanciful scenario? Consider the 2002 French presidential election.
  In the first round the Gaullist (right) candidate Chirac won ~20% of
  the vote. The far-right candidate Le Pen won 16.86%. The Socialist
  candidate Jospin came third with 16.18% of the vote and was
  eliminated. Various less popular candidates of the left won a total of
  28.59% of the first-round vote, but all these were also eliminated.

  Chirac beat Le Pen 82%-to-18% in the second round (one campaign poster
  read: "vote for the crook, not the fascist"). Had Jospin entered the
  second round instead of Le Pen, who knows whether Jospin would have
  defeated Chirac? It is probable that the French electorate would have
  preferred Jospin to Chirac and indeed *every* other presidential
  candidate.

  If so, it seems undesirable that the two round system did not elect
  Jospin.

